WEBVTT

00:00:05.250 --> 00:00:08.667
In this section you will learn to interpret a work plan;

00:00:08.667 --> 00:00:11.125
Make a 360 degree scan;

00:00:11.125 --> 00:00:14.667
Incorporate government priorities into a work plan;

00:00:14.667 --> 00:00:18.333
And adjust a work plan according to new information.

00:00:18.917 --> 00:00:22.625
This section should take you approximately 20 minutes to complete.

00:00:26.375 --> 00:00:28.291
A work plan is a living document

00:00:28.291 --> 00:00:32.166
in which you define and prioritize your unit’s activities.

00:00:32.166 --> 00:00:34.667
Think of it as a to-do list for the upcoming year.

00:00:34.667 --> 00:00:38.208
It helps you to communicate how you’ll be assigning resources

00:00:38.208 --> 00:00:40.208
and managing timelines.

00:00:40.208 --> 00:00:43.542
It’s the cornerstone of your planning process because

00:00:43.542 --> 00:00:47.083
it supports your budget and reporting activities.

00:00:47.125 --> 00:00:49.834
Typically, you wouldn’t start from scratch.

00:00:49.834 --> 00:00:53.959
You would simply review last year's work plan, budget and reports

00:00:53.959 --> 00:00:56.542
to identify what needs to be kept,

00:00:56.542 --> 00:00:57.625
added

00:00:57.625 --> 00:01:00.083
or removed for the new year.

00:01:00.083 --> 00:01:02.583
But even before putting together your work plan,

00:01:02.583 --> 00:01:06.709
it’s useful to step out of your role and look at the big picture.

00:01:10.375 --> 00:01:12.750
It all starts with the Speech from the Throne,

00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:15.083
which outlines government priorities.

00:01:15.166 --> 00:01:18.625
These priorities will cascade down to you as a manager,

00:01:18.625 --> 00:01:21.834
and will need to be reflected in your work plan.

00:01:21.834 --> 00:01:23.500
After the Speech from the Throne,

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:26.041
the Prime Minister addresses a mandate letter

00:01:26.041 --> 00:01:28.417
to each department’s minister.

00:01:28.417 --> 00:01:32.333
In it, the Prime Minister sets out their overall expectations

00:01:32.333 --> 00:01:34.709
and policy objectives.

00:01:36.875 --> 00:01:38.917
Every year, there is a federal budget,

00:01:38.917 --> 00:01:42.625
which sets Canada’s economic agenda for the year.

00:01:42.625 --> 00:01:45.625
Departments will have priorities and objectives

00:01:45.625 --> 00:01:49.667
that align to this agenda in addition to other core mandates.

00:01:49.667 --> 00:01:52.959
The organization’s core responsibilities, results,

00:01:52.959 --> 00:01:55.542
results indicators, and program inventory

00:01:55.542 --> 00:02:00.625
are outlined in a Departmental Results Framework – or “DRF”.

00:02:00.625 --> 00:02:04.375
Then there is the Departmental Plan, which outlines, amongst other things,

00:02:04.375 --> 00:02:08.208
an organization’s expenditure plans for the coming year.

00:02:08.208 --> 00:02:11.417
It includes in more detail the elements of the DRF,

00:02:11.417 --> 00:02:15.001
expected results, and associated resourcing requirements,

00:02:15.001 --> 00:02:17.750
covering a three-year period.

00:02:17.750 --> 00:02:22.000
Then you may have plans per sector, branch, and directorate.

00:02:22.875 --> 00:02:24.875
This is where your work plan comes in!

00:02:24.875 --> 00:02:26.417
You build your work plan

00:02:26.417 --> 00:02:30.041
around the activities that are the responsibility of your unit

00:02:30.041 --> 00:02:34.417
and this naturally ties back into the Departmental Plan and DRF.

00:02:38.750 --> 00:02:42.583
At this point, you might be wondering what a work plan looks like.

00:02:42.583 --> 00:02:45.125
Not all units use the same model.

00:02:45.125 --> 00:02:49.125
By talking to your colleagues and to folks in corporate planning and finance,

00:02:49.125 --> 00:02:52.834
you can find out which one is used in your office.

